comments.text: I think you are using the first iteration of Speed Paints. I don't know if the improved 2.0 would help with any of your issues. I have only used 1 contrast paint so far, right out of the pot, and with beaten up brushes only. I don't know if it would ruin the exact color, but have you tried the contrast medium to add moisture into the speed paint when it begins to dry? I know it's meant to thin them, but, if they are drying out super fast, perhaps it won't really thin the pigment as much? I would also double check your humidity level where you are painting. They do dry fast, though...

comments.text: Great message at the start of the video. In 2012, I tried to be a Competition Painter and painted a total of 8 models over the course of the whole year... and I really wasn't happy with any of them. The next year, 2013, was the first year I started doing my army focused approach that cuts some corners and focuses on getting the army done instead of doing the best I can on individual models... and I painted over 1000. I have since refined the process and paint to what I would call high tabletop, and average around 250 to 300ish models/terrain pieces per year.
